Introduction

The United States Drug Policy, which is underneath the umbrella of the Department of Justice, has historically varied dramatically and due to this it has sparked public discourse, debate, and hysteria for roughly the last hundred-twenty years. The first significant act/policy against drugs was the 1914 Harrison Narcotic Act. The 1914 Harrison Narcotic Act established mechanism’s for distribution of narcotic drugs along with various laws that conferred to the United States intention of regulating the manufacturing, distribution, and labels of pharmaceutical drugs (Fishman, Papazian, Gonzalez, Riches, & Gilson, 2004, p. 310; Sacco, 2014, p. 2). Oversea trade and import taxation were two of the primary principles of this policy due to the remnants of the Opium Wars between 1839 and 1844, because outside of this government authorities were essentially “turning a blind eye” on the addiction and were more worried about fiscal policy (i.e. import taxation).

Just over fifty years after the Harrison Act was implemented into law another significant drug policy was implemented after the drug effects both during and from the Vietnam War. The Controlled Substance Act of 1970 controls the current U.S. drug control system with the classification of drugs from Schedule I through V based on their individual abuse potential and medical utility (Fishman, Papazian, Gonzalez, Riches, & Gilson, 2004, p. 310). As a note for future discussion in this analysis, prescription drugs are classified as Schedule II as they have the highest potential for abuse. Continuing along the same lines as these example is the policy in which I will be analyzing, the Anti-Drug Abuse Acts of 1986 and 1988.

