The Anti-Drug Abuse Acts

The Anti-Drug Abuse Acts of 1986 and its broadening in 1988, with the hundreds of provisions within them, declared that this policy of the US Government was to create a drug-free America by 1995 (Burke, 1992, p. 571; Sacco, 2014, p. 9). Below one can easily deduce that there were more problems than the solutions or goals that were intended for this policy

Goals

The strategic aim of the U.S. Drug Policy is to control drug supply by eradication of domestic crops and international “hot spots” of drug production to reduce supply by strengthening border patrols, eliminating trafficking, and restricting the manufacturing and distribution of licit controlled substance (i.e. prescription drugs) (Burke, 1992, p. 572; Bertram and Sharpe, 1996, pp. 42-43, Catalano, 2009, p. 479). The need for this was and still is tenfold. Roughly 85 to 90% of all illegal drugs in the United States come from Mexico, Central America, and South America by boats, tunnels, submarines, airplanes and even human cadavers. Another major goal of the U.S. Drug Policy is to stem drug abuse and addiction, primarily of heroin and cocaine; however, other “hard drugs” such as methamphetamine and prescription drugs where –until recent history– considered outranked and obsolete (Bertram and Sharpe, 1996, p. 41). The key word here is “obsolete”, because this is where many of the current problems of the U.S. Drug Policy and drug addiction come from.

Problems

Social control measures in the drug policy arena are part of a larger trend toward over-criminalized (Burke, 1992, p. 575). The ramifications of this over policing are

