Rational Model

My choice to utilize the rational model in relation to the Drug Abuse Acts is based on its functionality and its in-depth use of both pragmatic and logical process. Another key attribute, which I will get in more depth later, is that the process in which the Abuse Acts and the multitude of other policies within the war on drugs illustrate irrational thoughts on top of irrational thoughts. When looking at the whole picture the war on drugs can be viewed as a failure to cover up another failure and so on. The rational model specifies the procedures involved in making well-considered rational decisions that maximize the attainment of goals (Anderson, p 135). Outside of this desired end result achievement, rationalism facilitates that the overall cost of the policy will not surpass the overall benefits of the policy; therefore, another of the primary goals is to optimize for efficiency for a positive cost saving return on the “investment” (Gortner, Nichols, and Ball, p 248). The below is a thorough list of what must be deliberated by policymakers when they select the rational model (Dye, p 31):

I. They must know all of the value preferences and their relative weights when introduced to society.
II. Know all of the possible alternatives to utilize when known and unknown variables arise throughout implementation and evaluation of the policy.
III. Know the consequences of all of those alternatives.
IV. Calculate the ratio of benefits to cost of each of the alternatives in order to still maximize the social gains.
V. Lastly, decision makers should choose the most efficient policy alternative that produces the greatest benefit over cost.

