Defense

The reason that I feel that this is the best policy model to use in order to best explain the minute advantages and major disadvantages primarily associated with the Anti-Drug Abuse Acts and ultimately the war on drugs are logical substances within it. The primary goal of the model is the maximum social gains that it provides with its logical patterns of thought, because it needs a complete understanding of the societal values that will be born both during and after policy implementation by strategically planning acceptable alternative amendments and new policies to display the policies validity even when an unknown variable populates. If asking the question of whether incarceration was better than assisted drug treatment, nine times out of ten the answer will be no because the question is irrational and the answer is rational.

Limitations

Like all other policy models, there are barriers that the rational model has to overcome. Unfortunately, because of these barriers many policymakers tend to stay away from utilizing it in the overall decision and policy making processes. One of its barriers is that there are conflicting benefits and costs because it can be difficult to make the policy beneficial to all groups, rather than just the group the policy is concentrated on. Another limitation is that government officials and administrators are only satisfying the current demand rather than the lasting maximum social gain (Dye, 1972, p. 33). Due to the overall complexity of planning, formulating, and implementing a policy with continual progress, the rational model takes a longer period to digest all possibilities and reciprocate counterbalances of them into the policy. Even with these limitations,

