Regulatory Policy

The Anti-Drug Abuse Acts are positioned in the regulatory policy spectrum. Regulatory policies impose restrictions, limitations, and prohibitions in order to control the behavior of individual people and groups of people (Anderson, 2015, p. 14). Regulatory policy and the control in which it gives can be slightly associated with Socialism and Dictatorship; however, much of the government platform was adopted from socialist society and the literature within it. Regulatory policies range from affirmative action to gun control and even acceptable person behavior (Anderson, 2015, p. 14). These policies can also conflict with other policies for either the same group or different groups of people depending on what its purpose and mission is.

The Anti-Drug Abuse Acts are built on regulations to hinder and eradicate drug abuse and this is a known fact; however, these acts are to stop the problem but not rehabilitate the people affected by it. This is not because the regulatory policies are failing; this is because the right policies were not logically or rationally processed for continuous success before they were implemented. By pairing together the rational model with regulatory policies a higher success rate will be met due to the forecasted maximum social gains articulated into the controls indicated by the policy. Further evidence in the coming section justifies that the failure of the anti-drug abuse acts and the war on drugs cannot be blamed on the regulations or the lack there of the absence of rational thought.

