Role Government Failures

The Anti-Drug Abuse Acts is overall considered a failure by many politicians and scholars alike feel that if more logical thought had been associated from when the issue was first identified or better yet acknowledged by the U.S. Government. From 1970 to 1975, two-thirds of the total US drug budget went to prevention, education and treatment before the cost proportion shrank to just 43% between 1976 and 1981 (Burke, 1992, p. 573). Following this trend, during Reagan’s administration between the years of 1981 and 1986, the largest increase in drug related law enforcement skyrocketed from $263 million to $605 million which represented 38% of federal drug enforcement expenditures (Burke, 1992, p. 573, Bertram and Sharpe, 1996, p. 43). Do these significant funding increases show that one –or for that matter– all of the policies that have been issued in the war on drugs have been successful and corrected failures of the policy before it?

I’ll wait while you ponder this for a while, as long as it is rational and not irrational thinking like America’s drug war czars continue to do! While you are rationally thinking, add the additional perspective on how much the war on drugs costs in relation to incarceration On average it costs $30,000 a year for each person incarcerated in the US Prison System and under the mandatory sentencing that increases per sentencing, a single addicted user can cost upwards of $1.2 million dollars with a total of 40 years being locked up (Caulkins and Reuter, 2006, p. 84).

