Conclusion

It is past time to gather greater resources together for further research and education to address the prescription drug crisis here in the United States. The war on drugs has been nothing more than an unneeded expense due to its complete failure (Friedman, Mateu-Gelabert, and Rossi, 2012, p. 1402; Akers, 1992, p. 282). A key note in this failure is that in some states if a person is convicted of drug related felony a lifetime ban on receiving welfare benefits, a ban on public housing, and ineligibility of higher-education funding (Mauer, Weimer, and Heymann, 2007, p. 11); therefore, the government gives up on drug addicts even though they are the ultimate provider / supplier of prescription drug regulations.

To stop the harm that opiate based prescription drugs are causing, the U.S. Government needs to rationally contemplate about a new policy that will actually help the people whom they

